{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9877,"record_hash":"sha256:5faab6ad55657c131f3d5a291060d069e4df22e67a2c752cd152c20265736561","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:35:06.089Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"**Answer**\\nGitButler should treat handoff provenance as a lightweight, review-facing ledger: stable IDs, human-readable summaries, links back to sessions/issues, and explicit “what changed since last handoff” state. Don’t overbuild SLSA-style supply-chain attestations for this feature; borrow the shape, not the ceremony.\\n\\n**Strong Prior Art**\\n\\n1. **GitHub PRs: timeline as the shared handoff surface**  \\n   GitHub PR reviews combine inline comments, suggestions, approvals, resolved threads, CODEOWNERS review requests, and merge gating in the PR timeline.  \\n   Source: [GitHub pull request reviews](https://docs.github.[REDACTED:entropy])  \\n   Learn: make handoff notes live where reviewers already look: branch/PR summary, timeline/comment, or GitButler equivalent. Avoid hidden-only metadata.\\n\\n2. **GitHub linked issues/branches: simple relationship metadata wins**  \\n   GitHub links PRs and branches to issues through descriptions, keywords, and sidebars. This is boring and useful.  \\n   Source: [GitHub linking PRs to issues](https://docs.github.com/en/issues/tracking-your-work-with-issues/using-issues/linking-a-pull-request-to-an-issue)  \\n   Learn: handoff should support first-class links: issue, PR, branch, session, task, prior handoff. Plain URLs plus structured IDs are enough.\\n\\n3. **GitHub rulesets: provenance needs explainable policy context**  \\n   Rulesets show why a branch/PR is blocked and expose active rules to readers/auditors.  \\n   Source: [GitHub rulesets](https://docs.github.[REDACTED:entropy])  \\n   Learn: include “review state” in handoff: required checks, stale approval risk, blocked-by, needs-owner-review. Handoff without mergeability context is half a map.\\n\\n4. **GitLab MRs: activity feed/system notes are audit-lite**  \\n   GitL\n[TRUNCATED]\nthroughs), [CodeRabbit PR chat](https://docs.coderabbit.ai/guide/chat)  \\n   Learn: generated handoff should be a stable, updateable top-level artifact: summary, files touched, risks, tests, open questions, next actions. Not a pile of scattered comments.\\n\\n11. **Graphite/Sapling stacked PRs: handoff must respect dependency shape**  \\n   Graphite emphasizes reviewing stacked PRs independently and bottom-up; Sapling links commits to PRs in stacks.  \\n   Sources: [Graphite stacked PR review practices](https://www.graphite.[REDACTED:entropy]), [Sapling stack PRs](https://sapling-scm.com/docs/git/sapling-stack/)  \\n   Learn: GitButler handoff should show branch dependencies and “review this first/after that” ordering. For virtual branches, this is core, not garnish.\\n\\n12. **SLSA/GitHub attestations: useful only as a conceptual boundary**  \\n   GitHub artifact attestations are cryptographically signed build provenance: repo, commit SHA, workflow, environment, triggering event.  \\n   Source: [GitHub artifact attestations](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/concepts/security/artifact-attestations)  \\n   Learn: don’t drag full supply-chain machinery into developer handoff. But do copy the principle: provenance should answer who/what/when/from-what-inputs/produced-what-output.\\n\\n**Recommendation For GitButler**\\nBuild a “handoff record” with:\\n\\n- Stable ID surviving rebase/branch movement.\\n- Human summary: goal, approach, key decisions, risks.\\n- Structured state: branch, base, head, changed files, tests run, open todos, dependency stack.\\n- Links: issue/PR/session/AI chat/review threads.\\n- Timeline: generated events separate from author notes.\\n- Export targets: PR body/comment, commit trailer pointer, GitButler UI.\\n- Update behavior: preserve previous handoff, show delta since last handoff.\\n\\nSkip cryptographic provenance for v1. The winning feature is not “tamper-proof.” It is “a tired teammate can safely continue this work in five minutes.”\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:35:06.089Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}